flowRoot.flowPara: GNOME 3's notifications system has been overhauled for 3.16. The previous Message Tray has been replaced by a new message list that provides straightforward access to previous notifications, and notification pop-ups (called "banners") have been repositioned in order to make them more noticeable and to prevent them from interfering with applications.

As with the previous notifications design, it is possible to quickly and directly respond to notifications through their pop-up banners. This allows you to do things like quickly snooze an alarm or reply to a chat message.

Saving power, shutting down and suspending.
Suspend sends a computer to sleep. Everything is saved, and the screen and other parts of the computer switch off to save power.
Laptops automatically suspend when the lid is closed. All types of computer will automatically suspend when they are not used for a period of time (this can be changed in the power settings).
These hints and tips help to make your battery last longer.
Suspend when you are not using your computer.
Reduce the screen brightness: the screen uses a lot of power.
Turn off hardware features, such as Bluetooth and Wi-Fi (you can do this in the power settings).
Make sure that the "Dim screen when inactive" and "Blank screen" power options are on.
You can manually suspend by opening the system menu from the top right of the screen and holding down the alt key.
Connecting to the internet through Wi-Fi (wireless) and wired connections.
To connect to a Wi-Fi (wireless) network, click the status menu at the top right of the screen, and then click Select Network.
From the list of available Wi-Fi networks, select the network you want to connect to, and click Connect to confirm.
Depending on the network configuration, you might have to enter a password or key.

"What's New" is a single page, which reuses content from the release notes (which are cut down and edited). The word "GNOME" should be replaced with that of the distribution.
Search box pulls results from user help, the configured search engine, and relevant community support sites.
Search results replace the browse by topic section.
Downstream help box allows distributions to link to their own support sites.
Getting started is envisioned as a short series of pages (approximately 8 in number).
Each getting page includes a short tutorial or two, accompanied by static images.

The rest of the system help is contained within a short list of 6-8 topic areas. Where possible, each topic area should be covered by a single page of help. Each page is highly structured, with frequent headings - these assist scanning and navigation.
System help is presented as being distinct from the help pages for the Settings app. However, content can be shared/duplicated where necessary.
